I now have a thorough understanding of the entire codebase. Here is the complete implementation plan.

---

## Implementation Plan: Custom Theme System

### Overview

The plan introduces three built-in themes (`t3-dark`, `t3-light`, `t3-midnight`) while maintaining full backwards compatibility with all existing consumers of `useTheme()`. The approach keeps `resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark"` intact, which is required by `DiffWorkerPoolProvider`, `ChatView`, `DiffPanel`, `ChatMarkdown`, and `ComposerPromptEditor`. No new dependencies are added, no build configuration changes.

---

### Step 1: `packages/shared/src/theme.ts` — Create new file

This is a pure TypeScript file with no imports, no dependencies, and no Effect.js. It follows the exact pattern of `shell.ts` (plain exports, no framework).

**Full file content:**

```typescript
export type ThemeId = "t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight";
export type ThemeSelection = ThemeId | "system";

export type ThemeColorTokens = {
  background: string;
  foreground: string;
  accent: string;
  sidebar: string;
  editor: string;
  terminal: string;
  statusBar: string;
};

export type ThemeDefinition = {
  id: ThemeId;
  label: string;
  colorScheme: "light" | "dark";
  tokens: ThemeColorTokens;
};

export const BUILT_IN_THEMES: readonly ThemeDefinition[] = [
  {
    id: "t3-light",
    label: "Light",
    colorScheme: "light",
    tokens: {
      background: "oklch(1.0 0 0)",
      foreground: "oklch(0.27 0 0)",
      accent: "oklch(0.488 0.217 264)",
      sidebar: "oklch(0.97 0 0)",
      editor: "oklch(1.0 0 0)",
      terminal: "oklch(0.98 0 0)",
      statusBar: "oklch(0.94 0 0)",
    },
  },
  {
    id: "t3-dark",
    label: "Dark",
    colorScheme: "dark",
    tokens: {
      background: "oklch(0.105 0 0)",
      foreground: "oklch(0.94 0 0)",
      accent: "oklch(0.588 0.217 264)",
      sidebar: "oklch(0.09 0 0)",
      editor: "oklch(0.085 0 0)",
      terminal: "oklch(0.08 0 0)",
      statusBar: "oklch(0.115 0 0)",
    },
  },
  {
    id: "t3-midnight",
    label: "Midnight",
    colorScheme: "dark",
    tokens: {
      background: "oklch(0.07 0.018 264)",
      foreground: "oklch(0.92 0.008 264)",
      accent: "oklch(0.65 0.24 264)",
      sidebar: "oklch(0.055 0.018 264)",
      editor: "oklch(0.05 0.015 264)",
      terminal: "oklch(0.04 0.01 264)",
      statusBar: "oklch(0.065 0.018 264)",
    },
  },
] as const;

export const DEFAULT_THEME_ID: ThemeId = "t3-dark";

export function getBuiltInTheme(id: ThemeId): ThemeDefinition {
  const found = BUILT_IN_THEMES.find((t) => t.id === id);
  if (!found) {
    throw new Error(`Unknown theme id: ${id}`);
  }
  return found;
}

export function isThemeId(value: string): value is ThemeId {
  return value === "t3-dark" || value === "t3-light" || value === "t3-midnight";
}

export function isThemeSelection(value: string): value is ThemeSelection {
  return value === "system" || isThemeId(value);
}

/**
 * Maps a legacy localStorage value ("light", "dark") to a ThemeSelection.
 * Returns null if the value is already a valid ThemeSelection (no migration needed).
 */
export function migrateLegacyThemeValue(raw: string): ThemeSelection | null {
  if (raw === "light") return "t3-light";
  if (raw === "dark") return "t3-dark";
  return null;
}
```

**Color token rationale:**
- `t3-light` tokens pull directly from what the existing `:root` CSS block renders at runtime. The `background` is white (`oklch(1.0 0 0)`), `foreground` is neutral-800 equivalent, `sidebar` is a slightly off-white.
- `t3-dark` tokens reflect what the existing `@variant dark` block renders: `background` is near `color-mix(in srgb, neutral-950 95%, white)` ≈ `oklch(0.105 0 0)`.
- `t3-midnight` tokens are exactly as specified in the requirements.
- The `accent` tokens use the actual `--primary` oklch values already in the CSS file: `oklch(0.488 0.217 264)` for light, `oklch(0.588 0.217 264)` for dark/midnight.

**Design decision flag:** The `tokens` object in `ThemeDefinition` stores CSS color strings. These are used only by `ThemeSelector` for color swatch display — they are NOT used to drive the actual CSS custom properties. The CSS is the source of truth for rendering. The tokens exist purely as a visual reference for the UI. If you want them to also drive the CSS directly (replacing the static CSS class mechanism), that is a larger scope change not required here.

---

### Step 2: `packages/shared/package.json` — Add `"./theme"` export

Add one entry to the `exports` map. The pattern matches all existing entries exactly:

```json
"./theme": {
  "types": "./src/theme.ts",
  "import": "./src/theme.ts"
}
```

No other changes. No build step is added.

---

### Step 3: `apps/web/src/index.css` — Add new CSS variables and `.t3-midnight` class

Three changes in this file:

**3a. Add new semantic variables to `:root` (light values), after `--warning-foreground`:**

```css
  --sidebar-bg: oklch(0.97 0 0);
  --editor-bg: oklch(1.0 0 0);
  --terminal-bg: oklch(0.98 0 0);
  --status-bar-bg: oklch(0.94 0 0);
```

**3b. Add the same variables inside the existing `@variant dark { ... }` block, after `--warning-foreground` in that block:**

```css
    --sidebar-bg: oklch(0.09 0 0);
    --editor-bg: oklch(0.085 0 0);
    --terminal-bg: oklch(0.08 0 0);
    --status-bar-bg: oklch(0.115 0 0);
```

**3c. Add the `.t3-midnight` class block, placed immediately after the closing `}` of `:root` (after line 121), before the `body` rule at line 123:**

```css
.t3-midnight {
  --background: oklch(0.07 0.018 264);
  --foreground: oklch(0.92 0.008 264);
  --card: oklch(0.09 0.018 264);
  --card-foreground: oklch(0.92 0.008 264);
  --popover: oklch(0.09 0.018 264);
  --popover-foreground: oklch(0.92 0.008 264);
  --primary: oklch(0.65 0.24 264);
  --primary-foreground: oklch(1.0 0 0);
  --secondary: --alpha(oklch(0.65 0.24 264) / 8%);
  --secondary-foreground: oklch(0.92 0.008 264);
  --muted: --alpha(oklch(1.0 0 0) / 5%);
  --muted-foreground: oklch(0.65 0.008 264);
  --accent: --alpha(oklch(0.65 0.24 264) / 10%);
  --accent-foreground: oklch(0.92 0.008 264);
  --border: --alpha(oklch(1.0 0 0) / 7%);
  --input: --alpha(oklch(1.0 0 0) / 9%);
  --ring: oklch(0.65 0.24 264);
  --sidebar-bg: oklch(0.055 0.018 264);
  --editor-bg: oklch(0.05 0.015 264);
  --terminal-bg: oklch(0.04 0.01 264);
  --status-bar-bg: oklch(0.065 0.018 264);
}
```

**Important note on class application strategy:**
- `t3-light`: remove `.dark`, remove `.t3-midnight` from `<html>`
- `t3-dark`: add `.dark`, remove `.t3-midnight` from `<html>`
- `t3-midnight`: add `.dark` AND add `.t3-midnight` to `<html>`
- `system` resolving to light: same as `t3-light`
- `system` resolving to dark: same as `t3-dark` (no midnight for system)

The `.t3-midnight` rule does NOT need to be scoped under `.dark` because it only ever gets applied alongside `.dark`. The two classes are always set together. The Tailwind `@custom-variant dark (&:is(.dark, .dark *))` selector continues to work normally.

---

### Step 4: `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` — Replace existing file entirely

This is the core of the change. The existing file is a clean, self-contained module-level store using `useSyncExternalStore`. The new version follows exactly the same pattern but handles `ThemeId | "system"` instead of `"light" | "dark" | "system"`.

**Full replacement content:**

```typescript
import { useCallback, useEffect, useSyncExternalStore } from "react";
import {
  type ThemeSelection,
  type ThemeId,
  isThemeSelection,
  migrateLegacyThemeValue,
  getBuiltInTheme,
} from "@t3tools/shared/theme";

// Re-export types that consumers may use
export type { ThemeSelection, ThemeId };

const STORAGE_KEY = "t3code:theme";
const MEDIA_QUERY = "(prefers-color-scheme: dark)";

type ThemeSnapshot = {
  selection: ThemeSelection;
  systemDark: boolean;
};

let listeners: Array<() => void> = [];
let lastSnapshot: ThemeSnapshot | null = null;

function emitChange() {
  for (const listener of listeners) listener();
}

function getSystemDark(): boolean {
  return window.matchMedia(MEDIA_QUERY).matches;
}

function getStored(): ThemeSelection {
  const raw = localStorage.getItem(STORAGE_KEY);
  if (!raw) return "system";

  // Migration: map old "light"/"dark" values to new ThemeIds
  const migrated = migrateLegacyThemeValue(raw);
  if (migrated) {
    // Write migrated value back so next read is clean
    localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, migrated);
    return migrated;
  }

  if (isThemeSelection(raw)) return raw;
  return "system";
}

function applyTheme(selection: ThemeSelection, suppressTransitions = false) {
  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.classList.add("no-transitions");
  }

  const isDark =
    selection === "t3-dark" ||
    selection === "t3-midnight" ||
    (selection === "system" && getSystemDark());

  const isMidnight = selection === "t3-midnight";

  document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", isDark);
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle("t3-midnight", isMidnight);

  if (suppressTransitions) {
    // Force reflow so no-transitions takes effect before removal
    // oxlint-disable-next-line no-unused-expressions
    document.documentElement.offsetHeight;
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      document.documentElement.classList.remove("no-transitions");
    });
  }
}

// Apply immediately on module load to prevent flash
applyTheme(getStored());

function getSnapshot(): ThemeSnapshot {
  const selection = getStored();
  const systemDark = selection === "system" ? getSystemDark() : false;

  if (
    lastSnapshot &&
    lastSnapshot.selection === selection &&
    lastSnapshot.systemDark === systemDark
  ) {
    return lastSnapshot;
  }

  lastSnapshot = { selection, systemDark };
  return lastSnapshot;
}

function subscribe(listener: () => void): () => void {
  listeners.push(listener);

  const mq = window.matchMedia(MEDIA_QUERY);
  const handleChange = () => {
    if (getStored() === "system") applyTheme("system", true);
    emitChange();
  };
  mq.addEventListener("change", handleChange);

  const handleStorage = (e: StorageEvent) => {
    if (e.key === STORAGE_KEY) {
      applyTheme(getStored(), true);
      emitChange();
    }
  };
  window.addEventListener("storage", handleStorage);

  return () => {
    listeners = listeners.filter((l) => l !== listener);
    mq.removeEventListener("change", handleChange);
    window.removeEventListener("storage", handleStorage);
  };
}

export function useTheme() {
  const snapshot = useSyncExternalStore(subscribe, getSnapshot);
  const selection = snapshot.selection;

  // resolvedTheme stays "light" | "dark" for full backwards compatibility
  // with DiffWorkerPoolProvider, ChatView, DiffPanel, ChatMarkdown
  const resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark" = (() => {
    if (selection === "system") return snapshot.systemDark ? "dark" : "light";
    const def = getBuiltInTheme(selection);
    return def.colorScheme;
  })();

  // theme stays as ThemeSelection for the settings page
  const theme: ThemeSelection = selection;

  const setTheme = useCallback((next: ThemeSelection) => {
    localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, next);
    applyTheme(next, true);
    emitChange();
  }, []);

  // Keep DOM in sync on mount/change
  useEffect(() => {
    applyTheme(selection);
  }, [selection]);

  return { theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme } as const;
}
```

**Key backward-compat points:**
- `resolvedTheme` remains `"light" | "dark"` — unchanged type, unchanged semantics.
- `theme` changes type from `"light" | "dark" | "system"` to `ThemeSelection` (i.e., `"t3-dark" | "t3-light" | "t3-midnight" | "system"`). The settings page is the only consumer of `theme` directly (other files only use `resolvedTheme`), and the settings page will be updated in Step 6.
- `setTheme` parameter type changes from `Theme` to `ThemeSelection`. Only the settings page (Step 6) calls `setTheme`.
- Migration runs on `getStored()` every time, writing back immediately, so old users are upgraded transparently on first run.

**Design decision flag:** `getStored()` calls `migrateLegacyThemeValue` and writes back to `localStorage`. This means the migration is not a one-time event with a version guard — it runs every call until the value is valid. This is safe because `migrateLegacyThemeValue` only triggers on the exact strings `"light"` and `"dark"`, which will never be written by the new code. There is no need for a separate migration version key.

**Design decision flag:** `getBuiltInTheme(selection)` is called inside the `useTheme` hook synchronously in the render. This will throw if somehow an unknown ThemeId ends up in storage (e.g., a future theme that was removed). The `getStored()` guard with `isThemeSelection` protects against this — if the stored value is not a known ThemeSelection, it falls back to `"system"`. So `getBuiltInTheme` will only be called with a valid current `ThemeId`. This is safe.

---

### Step 5: `apps/web/src/components/ThemeProvider.tsx` — Create new file

This is a minimal wrapper component. Its job is to ensure the theme is applied on mount (the module-load side effect in `useTheme.ts` already handles the initial apply before React hydrates, but this component provides a React lifecycle guarantee for any edge cases like SSR or test environments).

```typescript
import { useEffect, type ReactNode } from "react";
import { useTheme } from "../hooks/useTheme";

interface ThemeProviderProps {
  children: ReactNode;
}

/**
 * ThemeProvider ensures the theme is applied to the document root on mount
 * and keeps it in sync throughout the app lifecycle. Must be rendered inside
 * the React tree (i.e., inside RouterProvider's Wrap or in __root.tsx).
 */
export function ThemeProvider({ children }: ThemeProviderProps) {
  // useTheme's internal useEffect handles DOM sync.
  // This component exists as an explicit mount boundary.
  useTheme();
  return <>{children}</>;
}
```

**Design decision flag:** The `ThemeProvider` is intentionally thin. Since `useTheme.ts` already does all DOM manipulation via the module-level `applyTheme(getStored())` side effect on load, the provider is mostly declarative scaffolding. Its primary value is as a named mounting point in the component tree, making the intent clear in `__root.tsx`. If you need the provider to pass theme context down (e.g., to avoid prop drilling), you could add a React context here — but since the existing codebase has all consumers calling `useTheme()` directly (not via context), this is not needed.

---

### Step 6: `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx` — Create new file

This component replaces the inline `THEME_OPTIONS` radio group in the settings page. It renders a visual card for each theme with a color swatch strip.

```typescript
import { type ThemeSelection, BUILT_IN_THEMES } from "@t3tools/shared/theme";
import { useTheme } from "../hooks/useTheme";
import { cn } from "~/lib/utils";

const THEME_SELECTOR_OPTIONS: Array<{
  value: ThemeSelection;
  label: string;
  description: string;
}> = [
  {
    value: "system",
    label: "System",
    description: "Match your OS appearance setting.",
  },
  {
    value: "t3-light",
    label: "Light",
    description: "Always use the light theme.",
  },
  {
    value: "t3-dark",
    label: "Dark",
    description: "Always use the dark theme.",
  },
  {
    value: "t3-midnight",
    label: "Midnight",
    description: "Deep blue-black dark variant.",
  },
];

interface ThemeSelectorProps {
  className?: string;
}

export function ThemeSelector({ className }: ThemeSelectorProps) {
  const { theme, setTheme } = useTheme();

  return (
    <div className={cn("space-y-2", className)} role="radiogroup" aria-label="Theme preference">
      {THEME_SELECTOR_OPTIONS.map((option) => {
        const selected = theme === option.value;
        // For "system" we show no swatches; for theme IDs we show the token colors
        const themeId = option.value !== "system" ? option.value : null;
        const tokens = themeId ? BUILT_IN_THEMES.find((t) => t.id === themeId)?.tokens : null;

        return (
          <button
            key={option.value}
            type="button"
            role="radio"
            aria-checked={selected}
            className={cn(
              "flex w-full items-start justify-between rounded-lg border px-3 py-2 text-left transition-colors",
              selected
                ? "border-primary/60 bg-primary/8 text-foreground"
                : "border-border bg-background text-muted-foreground hover:bg-accent",
            )}
            onClick={() => setTheme(option.value)}
          >
            <span className="flex flex-col gap-1.5">
              <span className="flex items-center gap-2">
                {tokens ? (
                  <span
                    className="inline-flex h-3.5 w-10 shrink-0 overflow-hidden rounded-sm border border-black/10"
                    aria-hidden="true"
                  >
                    {/* Background swatch */}
                    <span
                      className="flex-1"
                      style={{ background: tokens.background }}
                    />
                    {/* Sidebar swatch */}
                    <span
